Setting up the data

Topic 0 = Other; 1 = Health

Incentives 0 = No; 1 = Yes

# Make type and level labels
# type_all and level_all include the mode, to be used on data_net
type_all   <- c("g", "g", "g", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c")
levels_all <- c(1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 2, 2, 2, 3, 5)

# type and levels do not include mode are for the split data
type   <- c("g", "g", "g", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c", "c")
levels <- c(1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 2, 2, 2, 3)

# Make a list of the data sets
# all data
data_net_list <- list(data = data_net, type = type_all, level = levels_all, colnames = colnames(data_net))
# data split by modes
f2f_net_list  <- list(data = f2f_net,  type = type, level = levels, colnames = colnames(f2f_net))
web_net_list  <- list(data = web_net,  type = type, level = levels, colnames = colnames(web_net))
mail_net_list <- list(data = mail_net, type = type, level = levels, colnames = colnames(mail_net))
tel_net_list  <- list(data = tel_net,  type = type, level = levels, colnames = colnames(tel_net))

# checks

length(levels_all)

Moderated MGM

Here I make a moderated MGM (for interest), which is in theory equivalent to partitioning the data on mode.

## Note that the sign of parameter estimates is stored separately; see ?mgm

set.seed(123)

mgm_tel <- mgm(data       = as.matrix(tel_net_list$data), 
               type       = tel_net_list$type,
               level      = tel_net_list$levels,
               k          = 2,
               lambdaSel  = 'EBIC', 
               lambdaGam  = 0.25,
               ruleReg    = "OR",
               binarySign = TRUE,
               scale      = TRUE, 
               pbar       = FALSE)
## Note that the sign of parameter estimates is stored separately; see ?mgm
# Predictability of nodes
mgm_predict_tel <- predict(object   = mgm_tel,
                           data     = tel_net_list$data, 
                           errorCat = 'nCC',
                           errorCon = 'R2')

errors <- list()
for(i in 1:3)  errors[[i]] <- mgm_predict_tel$errors[i,2]
for(i in 4:10) errors[[i]] <- mgm_predict_tel$errors[i,3]

colors <- list()
for(i in 1:3)  colors[[i]] <- "#90B4D4"
for(i in 4:10) colors[[i]] <- c("#FFA500", "#FF4300")

qgraph(input       = mgm_tel$pairwise$wadj,
       layout      = 'circle',
       edge.color  = mgm_tel$pairwise$edgecolor,
       nodeNames   = nice_colnames[1:10],
       edge.labels = TRUE, edge.label.cex = 0.7, edge.label.bg = TRUE,
       legend.cex  = .45,
       pie        = errors, # provide errors as input
       pieColor   = colors)

       #filetype    = "png",
       #filename    = "img/mgm_tel_preds",
       #bg          = "transparent")

  • Nonresponse and bias are connected, where a unit increase in nonresponse causes a 0.19 unit increase in bias.
  • Mode appears to be the most central mode in the network, since it has many (strong) connections.
  • Mode is connected both to bias and nonresponse rate, but the latter more strongly:
    • Bias reduces by 0.04 units when the survey mode is paper, compared to f2f (reference).
    • Bias reduces by 0.04 when the question type is unobservable (compared to demographic) - confusing ?
    • Nonresponse decreases 1.22 for mail, 0.34 for paper, and 0.47 for telephone, relative to f2f.
    • Over years, there are more f2f and weeb surveys, less mail and telephone (makes sense).
    • Higher chance of being salient if the survey is mail, else web is less salient.
    • F2F and web surveys incentivised less than mail, paper, telephone.
    • Reminders more often sent for F2F and web surveys.
    • Telephone surveys more often sponsored.
    • F2F and paper more likely to be health surveys
    • F2F and telephone more likely to be aimed at special population

  • Bias decreases 0.29 if a f2f survey is salient to the respondent
  • Bias decreases 0.42 if a f2f survey uses incentives
  • As bias increases, the probability of survey not detailing reminders increases 0.85
  • Bias decreases -0.097 in health surveys.
  • As bias increases, question type is less likely to be demographic.
  • NR decreases 2.29 if a survey is salient
  • NR increases 2.69 if a survey uses reminders, and by 0.86 for undetermined
  • NR increases 1.03 for health surveys
  • NR increases 1.73 if survey is for a special population
  • NR increases 0.74 for observable questions / decreases for demographic
